DateReviewed: 2026-05-05
Description: This article dives into why your Kubernetes platform team is still answering tickets. They start with a scenario - new features needs a namespace - and how that happens or actually falls short. They claim it isn't a staffing or infra issue, but rather an understanding of process one. He's suggests that NaaS - namespaces as a service - will give devs what they want, a way to deploy in a timely manner. They talk a bit about the landscape, and some of the various failures that make up the reason this needs to happen. They note that not even security and policy tools are targets. Their big point is that automation without good policy will just create sprawl and confusion, but faster than you can keep up. They argue that you build the policy first, and then allow names and require labels as needed. The goal here is to have resources created consistently, quickly, and withing your governance guidelines. They dive more deeply and explain a lot - it's a very well written piece.
BottomLine: Solid piece about building good automation on strong policy and governance pieces
